{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492727"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:42:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:42:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1140"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1140"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0.11,0.03,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1140"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90281"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1140"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1140"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74534"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40761"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90281"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old teacher presents with a two week history of constant dull right subcostal pain. She is normally in good health and has recently returned to Australia from a two year secondment in Istanbul. She does not use any medications and does not smoke. She drinks about two glasses of wine on weekends. On examination she looks well and there are no abnormal physical findings. Her BMI is 24. An ultrasound examination is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydatid disease","Liver abscess","Acute cholecystitis","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Haemangioma of the liver"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are at least three separate lesions in the liver and one is clearly septated. The septate appearance in characteristic of an \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E. Hydatid disease is endemic in many parts of the world, including Turkey. Whilst the cysts are often no more than incidental findings, as they increase in size, the cysts can produce pain. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eabscess\u003C/strong\u003E on ultrasound tends to be poorly marginated, hypoechoic to adjacent parenchyma and may contain internal liquid and gas. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemangioma\u003C/strong\u003E on ultrasound is classically well marginated, poorly vascular and echogenic to adjacent parenchyma. An \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E would occur classically in a cirrhotic liver and appear as a solid mass often with internal vascularity and with adjacent vascular invasion. Most haemangiomas of the liver are incidental findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gallbladder is not visible on this particular part of the ultrasound examination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A liver cyst with a septate appearance is virtually diagnostic of hydatid disease."],"references":["Marrero JA, Ahn J, Reddy KR. ACG Clinical Guideline: The Diagnosis and Management of Focal Liver Lesions.Am J Gastroenterology 2014; doin:10.1038"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74534"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1140"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18391"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18391"},"att